ISYE 6402 Homework 6 Template

Background

Individuals stock prices tend to exhibit high amounts of non-constant variance, and thus ARIMA models build upon that data would likely exhibit non-constant variance in residuals. In this problem we are going to analyze the Tesla stock price data from 2011 through end of July 2021. We will use the ARIMA-GARCH to model daily and weekly stock price (adjusted close price at the end of a day for daily data or at the end of the week for weekly data), with a focus on the behavior of its volatility as well as forecasting both the price and the volatility.

#Question 1: Exploratory Data Analysis (20 points)

1a. Based on your intuition, when would you use daily vs weekly stock price data? Response: As stock price fluctuates by seconds, usually when looking for a short-term trading or day trading, I would look at the price variation within a shorter term to time in the market; while when looking for long term investment, analyzing the weekly stock price is computationally less expensive and makes more sense to examine the trend. In sum, when doing a shorter term/day trading, I would look at the daily stock price; when investing for longer term, swing trading or long term investing, I would look at the weekly price data.

1b. Plot the time series plots comparing daily vs weekly data. How do the daily vs weekly time series data compare?

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
ts.plot(TSLADaily, main="Daily vs Weekly TSLA price")
lines(TSLAWeekly,col="red")

Response: Weekly vs Montly Time Series data comparison The daily price is more volatile than the weekly price data, especially after 2020. In year of 2020, We saw several deeper dips and sharper increases in TESLA daily price than those in weekly price. Prior to 2020, there’s not much difference as TESLA price overall was not as volatile as it turned to be after 2020. We can tell the more volatile the stovk is, the more precise the daily price can capture its trend.

Analyzing weekly and daily data with trend fitting

#daily

Response: Weekly vs Montly Time Series data trend fit Prior to 2020, the daily and weekly fitted data trend almost overlays perfectly. After 2020, as the TSLA price turned to be more volatile and spiked dramatically, the weekly fitted data reflects the shorter term trend more precisely than the weekly trend. Also, the price got extremely volatile within a shorter term, hence daily has a higher value than the weekly data.

#Fitting ARIMA model    
  final.aic=Inf
    final.order=c(0,0,0)
    for (p in 0:8) for (d in 1:2) for (q in 0:8) 
    {
        current.aic=AIC(arima(train.daily,order=c(p, d, q),method="ML"))
        if(current.aic<final.aic)

            final.aic=current.aic

Response: Prediction Comparison For MAPE, the lower the better. Daily MAPE is 0.039, while weekly MAPE is 0.01; this shows that weekly prediction is more accurate than the daily prediction. Since MAPE is commonly used but not appropriate to evaluate prediction accuracy for most time serie models, here to look at the PM. PM measures the proportion between the variability in the prediction and the variability in the test data; and the lower the better ; hence the daily PM of 5.04 shows poor prediction. As there’s only one prediction in weekly data, we are unable to calculate the PM.

Response:ARMA GARCH residual analysis for the Weekly and daily Data

The box test for residual DAILY Tesla price model (AMRA(0,1)-GARCH(1,1) )show p>0.05, we failed to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the data values are independent. The squared daily residuals has a small p value, rejecting the null hypothesis that the time series isn’t auto correlated.

The box test of weekly model (ARMA(4,2)-GARCH(1,1))show p<0.05, so does the squared weekly residuals. Also ACF and PACF of squared weekly &daily residuals do not resemble the white noises, suggesting a higher order GARCH model may be considered.

#Question 4: Reflection on the Modeling and Forecasting (10 points)

Based on the analysis above, discuss the application of ARIMA on the stock price versus the application of ARMA-GARCH on the stock return. How do the model fit the data? How well do the model predict? How do the models perform when using daily versus weekly data? Would you use one approach over another for different settings? What are some specific points of caution one would need to consider when applying those models?

Response: Final considerations The ARIMA model assumes the constant variance and ARMA-GARCH model can model the non constant variance. When it comes to the stock analysis, volatility is one of the major factors to predict the future trends hence a model that factors in the consonant variance is usually more appropriate to forecast the trend.

In this example, daily ARIMA(8,1,7) and weekly ARIMA(8,2,8) ignores the variance effect hence underestimated the data. The daily ARMA(0,1)-GARCH(1,1) and weekly ARMA(4,2)-GARCH(1,1) captures the volatility better but higher GARCH may be considered. When comparing the daily vs weekly data performance, overall I see a better performance in weekly data in both models. This is because ARIMA model ignores variance, it can be used to predict very short term data and as effective as ARMA-GARCH; since we are simply looking at one week data, the performance of ARIMA is not significantly worse than ARMA-GARCH. Depending on the predicting time period, the type of the stocks, I would use different approach over another. As stated, ARIMA can be computational less expensive hence when making a short-term price prediction on a stable stock price with no huge volatility, I would consider ARIMA model; otherwise, I could use a joint model to capture variance. To sum, there are a couple specific points when considering selecting models to predict stock price: 1） Time horizon; 2) volatility; 3) mean; 4) computational expensive or not; 5) prediction accuracy.
